type AggregationFeatures : <"The aggregation operation to be applied for resolving multiple values of the object for which this attribute is populated, into one value. The aggregationMethod represents a enumerated list of functional operations, all commutative, of type : [ F(X0, X1, X2, ...Xn) = Y ] where : [X1], [X2], ..., X[Xn] are values of the parent object and [Y] is the unique output value after resolving, and: [F] is the applicable operation e.g. Sum, Multiply, Min, Max, Average. The aggregationMethod is processing either values in array, else dated values in time series. Besides, multiple aggregation or ranking are composable in sorted manner with the compoundedAggregation attribute (considering a matrix of dateValue with observable in row and date in column for instance, then any combination of vertical or horizontal aggreation can be represented). Optionnaly, a rankingMethod may be defined prior to aggregating the values, say for representing so-called 'rainbow' features in some derivatives products (example : net payout consisting in ranking the 1th, the 2nd and the 3rd performance among multiple ones being compared, usually with distinct weight per rank, before being aggregated to calculate the final value)."> // FORK
      [metadata key]

    aggregationMethod AggregationMethod (1..1) <"Defines the method in which multiple values can be aggregated into a single value. It is a set of commutative functions  e.g. Sum, Multiply, Min, Max, Average. Importantly, two dimensions may be considered when aggregating : value series resulting from an object with unbound cardinality, else multiple value resulting from dateValue series - hence an optional choice below between the attributes which represent each of these two dimentions :  valueSeriesAggregation or datedValueSeriesAggregation.">
    aggregationCalculationDate DateRelativeToEnum (0..1) <"The enumerated values to specify the type of date to be used as an anchor.">
    compoundedAggregation AggregationFeatures (0..1) <"Permits to compound valueAggregation series in sorted manner, assuming that sorting order shall be read from the left end-value to the right start-value of the nested series e.g. say aggregationMethod(a) shall be applied first then aggregationMethod(b) shall apply to the calculatedValue(a), then one shall represent such loop as aggregationMethod(b)->aggregationLoop->aggregationMethod(a). As indication, such 'left-to-right' interpretation of nesting series is straight applicaiton of the base set theory interpretation per which the embedded inclusion of parties sets within each others is per se an ordering expression e.g. given sets of parties (a) and ((a),b) then considering embedded inclusions would result in resolving (a) as being the start value and ((a),b) being the subsequent value.">
    observationTerms ObservationTerms (0..1)
        [metadata address]
    bespokeExpression BespokeExpression (0..1) <"Any bespoke name or description that may be specified.">
    calculatedValue CalculationValue (0..1) <"The numerical value or dated value which corresponds to the resolved value of the parent object for which this attribute is populated e.g. output from valueOperator or aggregationOperator.">
        [metadata reference]

type StructuringFeatures:  // FORK_3
    [metadata key]

    knockEvent KnockEvent (0..*) <"Represents the functional operation [ F(X,In) = X * (Boolean) ] or the functional operation [ F(X,Out) = X * (1 - Boolean) ] where : [In] or [Out] designates the knockType, [Boolean] equals [1] when the trigger condition is verified as true, else equals [0], and [X] is the value of the object for which KnockEvent is defined as an attribute. Accordingly, this specifies that the existence of the parent object is contigent, either because it does not exists by default (therefore has no economic effect) until the condition is verified as true, which is defined as the Knock-In type, else because it does exist by default (has economic effect) unless the condition is verified as true, which is defined as the Knock-Out type.">
            [metadata reference]
    capFloor CapFloor (0..*) <"Represents the functional operation [ F(X,Cap) = min(X,Cap) ] or the functional operation [ F(X,Floor) = max(X,Floor) ] where : [Cap] or [Floor] is the value of the barrier level, and [X] is the value of the object for which CapFloor is defined as an attribute. As an indication, most use case consits in defining only one Cap or one Floor or both. Howerver, it is permitted to populate more instances based on the condition that some of such instances have knock event attribute meaning some of them are contingent e.g. ladder or lock-in features : cap or floor series are defined on top of observable price, but they are only activated if the price has touched the fixed levels.">
            [metadata reference]
    algebraicOperator AlgebraicOperator (0..1)
            [metadata reference]

type AlgebraicOperator : <"The aggregation operation to be applied for resolving multiple values of the object for which this attribute is populated, into one value. The aggregationMethod represents a enumerated list of functional operations, all commutative, of type : [ F(X0, X1, X2, ...Xn) = Y ] where : [X1], [X2], ..., X[Xn] are values of the parent object and [Y] is the unique output value after resolving, and: [F] is the applicable operation e.g. Sum, Multiply, Min, Max, Average. The aggregationMethod is processing either values in array, else dated values in time series. Besides, multiple aggregation or ranking are composable in sorted manner with the compoundedAggregation attribute (considering a matrix of dateValue with observable in row and date in column for instance, then any combination of vertical or horizontal aggreation can be represented). Optionnaly, a rankingMethod may be defined prior to aggregating the values, say for representing so-called 'rainbow' features in some derivatives products (example : net payout consisting in ranking the 1th, the 2nd and the 3rd performance among multiple ones being compared, usually with distinct weight per rank, before being aggregated to calculate the final value)."> // FORK_3
      [metadata key]

    baseValue OperatorValue (0..1)
    operandValue OperatorValue (0..1)
    operator AlgebraicOperationEnum (0..1)
    knockEvent KnockEvent (0..1)
    bespokeExpression BespokeExpression (0..1) <"Any bespoke name or description that may be specified.">
    calculationDate DateRelativeToEnum (0..1) <"The enumerated values to specify the type of date to be used as an anchor.">
    calculatedValue CalculationValue (0..1) <"The numerical value or dated value which corresponds to the resolved value of the parent object for which this attribute is populated.">
        [metadata reference]

    condition Operand:<"An operand value only applies by reference to an anchor value, which may be either a base value or a composite value.">
    if operandValue exists then baseValue exists

    condition NonCommutativeOperation:
    if (operator = AlgebraicOperationEnum  -> Subtract or operator = AlgebraicOperationEnum -> Divide)
        then operandValue exists
            else operandValue is absent

